FBIS3-4880 "dreas041__a94011" FBIS-EAS-94-041-A Document Type:Daily Report 2 March 1994 ANNEX Japan Hosokawa on Downing of Aircraft Over Bosnia OW0203125794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Mar 94 Evening Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY OW0203125794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN Language: Japanese Article Type:BFN [Text] Combat aircraft of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) shot down four military aircraft believed to be piloted by Serbs over Bosnia-Herzegovina. Asked by reporters in the Diet building on the morning of 1 March to comment on the incident, Prime Minister Hosokawa said: "NATO combat aircraft shot down the four military aircraft within the framework of the United Nations." In this way, the prime minister expressed his view that there was no problem with the action taken by NATO. Commenting on the incident at a news conference on 1 March after a cabinet session, Chief Cabinet Secretary Takemura said, "I understand the action was taken in accordance with a resolution adopted by the UN Security Council." At the news conference, the government spokesman issued a statement saying: "Although it is not known to which side the downed military aircraft belonged, we hope that parties to the conflict will comply with the resolution adopted by the UN Security Council and work to end the conflict."
